<div class="center"><div class="thumb tnone"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:442px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Electoral_map_2012-2020.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/Electoral_map_2012-2020.svg/440px-Electoral_map_2012-2020.svg.png" decoding="async" width="440" height="272" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/Electoral_map_2012-2020.svg/660px-Electoral_map_2012-2020.svg.png 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/Electoral_map_2012-2020.svg/880px-Electoral_map_2012-2020.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="959" data-file-height="593" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Electoral_map_2012-2020.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>This map shows the number of electors from each state for the 2012, 2016 and 2020 presidential elections. Following the 2010 census, eight states lost one electoral vote and two (New York and Ohio) each lost two electoral votes; six states gained one electoral vote, Florida gained two, and Texas gained four.</div></div></div></div>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Alternative_methods_of_choosing_electors">Alternative methods of choosing electors</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=United_States_Electoral_College&amp;action=edit&amp;section=25" title="Edit section: Alternative methods of choosing electors">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
