</li>
<li id="cite_note-42"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Electoral_College_(United_States)#cite_ref-42">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Presidential Elections 1789–1996. Congressional Quarterly, Inc. 1997, <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-5680-2065-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-1-5680-2065-5">978-1-5680-2065-5</a>, p.10-11</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-43"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Electoral_College_(United_States)#cite_ref-43">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Presidential Elections 1789–1996. Congressional Quarterly, Inc. 1997, <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-5680-2065-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-1-5680-2065-5">978-1-5680-2065-5</a>, p.11</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-44"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Electoral_College_(United_States)#cite_ref-44">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20130103115308/http://history.house.gov/Institution/Apportionment/Apportionment/">Apportionment by State (PDF)</a>, House of Representatives, History, Art &amp; Archives, viewed January 27, 2019. Unlike the votes taken in the Electoral College, from 1803 to 1846, the U.S. Senate sustained parity between free-soil and slave-holding states. But subsequently, an unbroken chain of free-soil states, including Iowa, Wisconsin, California, Minnesota, Oregon and Kansas, were admitted before the outbreak of the <a href="American_Civil_War" title="American Civil War">Civil War</a>.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-45"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Electoral_College_(United_States)#cite_ref-45">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="../../www.archives.gov/founding-docs/constitution-transcript">U.S. Constitution Transcript</a>, held at the U.S. National Archives, viewed online on February 5, 2019.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-46"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Electoral_College_(United_States)#cite_ref-46">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Brian D. Humes, Elaine K. Swift, Richard M. Valley, Kenneth Finegold, and Evelyn C. Fink, "Representation of the Antebellum South in the House of Representatives: Measuring the Impact of the Three-Fifths Clause" in David W. Brady and Mathew D. McCubbins, eds., Party, Process and Political Change in Congress: New Perspectives on the History of Congress (2002), Stanford University Press <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r951705291"/><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-8047-4571-0" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-8047-4571-0">978-0-8047-4571-0</a> p. 453, and Table 15.1, "Impact of the Three-Fifths Clause on Slave and Nonslave Representation (1790–1861)", p.454.</span>
